nachos

Class Debug

  • java.lang.Object
    • nachos.Debug

  • public class Debug
extends java.lang.Object
    This class contains debugging methods for generating user-selectable debugging printout and for placing assertions in the code that terminate execution and print debugging messages when they fail. Each method that generates debugging printout takes as its first parameter a character that classifies the type of debugging message being produced. The user can select which debugging printout will be generated by supplying the command line argument (-d) to Nachos. The argument immediately following the -d is a sequence of characters that specifies the classes of debugging messages that should be shown. If the sequence contains the character '+', then all debugging messages are shown, execept for those pertaining to simulation internals, which have to be enabled explicitly. Debugging messages of class '+' are always shown. Classes of debugging printout that currently exist in the code are: a Address translation and user memory access c Console d Disk f File system i Interrupts m User-mode execution n Network p Serial port s Synchronization t Threads and scheduling @ Simulation internals The easiest way to see which messages are which is to run Nachos with the arguments "-d +", which will show all debugging printout other than for simulation internals. You are also encouraged to add your own debugging flags. For example, you could use digits or upper-case letters, neither of which are used in the base system.

      • ASSERT

        public static void ASSERT(boolean condition)
        Equivalent of the C++ Nachos ASSERT macro. Comes to a screeching halt when the condition is false. (Nifty thing about the JVM is that it'll print out a full stack trace, automatically. All we have to do is throw an exception.)
        Parameters:
        condition - If false, the assertion fails and an exception is thrown.
